<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-316-584  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 316 584.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Design  March 12 1990 v29 n6 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Production advances hold down switcher prices.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thryft, Ann R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Low-power switching power supply vendors are pursuing severalmethods to reduce costs and improve technologies during the nextseveral years of forecast flat prices.andP;  The sizes of and pricesfor under-150W power supplies declined steadily the last fewyears, but the basic components have not achieved the integrationand consequent price and performance benefits that otherelectronics products have gained.andP;  Consequently, manufacturers areemploying such production strategies as surface-mount technologyand automated assembly to lower costs.andP;  Switching power supplymakers are also increasing the number of features of theirproducts (examples being universal inputs, higher density andremote sensing) while maintaining prices.andP;  Product developmentstrategies and products of several vendors are described.andO;Forthcoming alternative low-power switching technologies arediscussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Power SupplySwitchingIndustry AnalysisTrendsProductsManufacturersFuture TechnologiesPrice.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   Switching power supplies: cost per watt. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>